      "side": 1,
      "message": "\u003e Another way would be to get it from argv[0], which would mean having some sort of save of that at the top of main() in {test, non-test, Chromium}, which is a bit stinky.\n\nWe already have this: crashpad::test::InitializeMainArguments() (already called from our test main()) and crashpad::test::GetMainArguments(). Since it’s a test interface, you’d only be able to use it to implement TestPaths::Executable(), not Paths::Executable(). But given the quirks of argv[0] (next paragraph), it wouldn’t be suitable for a non-test interface anyway (and it’d only really be suitable for tests as a last resort, if there really isn’t any better way to do it.)\n\nThere’s no guarantee (on most systems, anyway) that argv[0] has anything to do with your executable, it’s just convention. And even the convention says only that argv[0] carries the thing that the user invoked, so, for example, when you type ls and PATH resolution finds /bin/ls, argv[0] is just ls.",
